<section
  id='case-semester-project-1'
  class='fullscreen-section'
  data-title='Case Study: Gemenskapet Science Museum — Web Development | Katja Turnsek'
  data-description='Responsive museum homepage built with semantic HTML and modern CSS, focusing on accessibility, clear information structure, playful visual design, and fast loading.'
  data-case='semester-project-1'
>
  <div class='rows'>
    <div class='row'>
      <h1>Web Development</h1>
      <h2>Gemenskapet Science Museum - Responsive Museum Website</h2>

      <div class='tech-demo-wrapper'>
        <div class='tech-stack'><strong>Tools:</strong> HTML | CSS</div>

        <!-- Reusable component: Demo Links -->
        <div class='demo-links' data-auto='demo' data-case='semester-project-1'></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class='row'>
      <!-- Reusable component: Project Switcher -->
      <nav
        class='project-switcher'
        aria-label='Gemenskapet Science Museum sections'
        data-auto='switcher'
        data-case='semester-project-1'
      ></nav>
    </div>

    <div class='row'>
      <h3>Objective</h3>
      <p>
        To build a playful but credible
        <strong>museum website</strong>
        for older children and young teens, using
        <strong>semantic HTML</strong>
        and
        <strong>modern CSS</strong>
        only. The focus was to present exhibits, events, and visitor information in a clear,
        responsive, and accessible way.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class='row'>
      <div class='case-study-columns'>
        <div class='case-study-wrapper'>
          <div class='case-study-text'>
            <h3>Development Focus</h3>
            <ul class='bullet-list'>
              <li>
                Built with
                <strong>semantic HTML</strong>
                using clear landmarks, structured headings, and accessible page flow
              </li>
              <li>
                Created a responsive layout with
                <strong>CSS Grid, Flexbox, and fluid spacing</strong>
              </li>
              <li>
                Designed a visual direction that feels
                <strong>curious, colorful, educational, and trustworthy</strong>
              </li>
              <li>
                Used rounded shapes, generous spacing, and a bright color palette to make the
                interface feel welcoming for a younger audience
              </li>
              <li>
                Focused on
                <strong>accessibility</strong>
                with readable contrast, focus states, descriptive labels, and useful alt text
              </li>
              <li>
                Kept the build
                <strong>HTML/CSS-only</strong>
                for fast loading, simple structure, and strong front-end fundamentals
              </li>
              <li>
                Planned the structure and visual system in
                <strong>Figma</strong>
                before building the final page
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class='case-study-wrapper'>
          <figure class='case-study-item item-right'>
            <img
              class='thumb'
              src='{{base}}assets/images/site-gemenskapet-science-museum-600.webp'
              data-src='site-gemenskapet-science-museum-600.webp'
              data-path='assets/images'
              alt='Gemenskapet Science Museum homepage desktop view showing colorful museum sections and visitor information'
            />
            <figcaption class='work-caption'>Desktop version - Homepage</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>

        <div class='case-study-wrapper'>
          <figure class='case-study-item item-left'>
            <img
              class='thumb'
              src='{{base}}assets/images/site-gemenskapet-science-museummobile-600.webp'
              data-src='site-gemenskapet-science-museummobile-600.webp'
              data-path='assets/images'
              alt='Gemenskapet Science Museum mobile homepage and menu view'
            />
            <figcaption class='work-caption'>Mobile version - Homepage and menu</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>

        <div class='case-study-wrapper'>
          <div class='case-study-text'>
            <h3>Key Features</h3>
            <ul class='bullet-list-right'>
              <li>
                <strong>Responsive homepage</strong>
                designed for desktop, tablet, and mobile screens
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Clear information structure</strong>
                for exhibits, events, opening hours, pricing, and location
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>CSS-only interface</strong>
                with no JavaScript dependency
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Accessible navigation</strong>
                with logical headings, labels, and keyboard-friendly structure
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Playful visual identity</strong>
                using color, shape, and spacing to support the museum theme
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class='row'>
      <h3>Reflection</h3>
      <p>
        Gemenskapet Science Museum strengthened my understanding of
        <strong>semantic structure, responsive CSS, accessibility, and visual hierarchy</strong>.
        Because the build used HTML and CSS only, every layout and interaction decision had to be
        solved through strong structure, careful spacing, and clear styling.
      </p>
      <p>
        The project also helped me balance a playful design direction with museum credibility. The
        colorful palette, rounded shapes, and friendly layout support a younger audience while still
        keeping the information easy to scan and understand.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class='back-to-work-container'>
      <a
        href='{{base}}#work'
        class='label-link back-to-work-label'
        data-back
        data-back-fallback='{{base}}#work'
        aria-label='Go back'
      >
        <svg class='icon icon-18 arrow-icon' aria-hidden='true'><use href='#i-arrow-left' /></svg>
        <span class='label-text'>Back to Work</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>